			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Well I did suggest in a list of things &gt;NES &lt;SNES <img src="./images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";)" title="Wink" /> <br /><br />but the issue with the MD and SNES is they are VBlanked limited, the Amiga has always on raw access to everywhere on the screen, you can also double/tripple buffer. So While the 3D in the Overdrive 2 demo for the MD was good for the MD, watch some A500 demos. The line drawing and poly-filling hardware allow it to do some unique stuff. A few games let you morph your character because its actually vector. Anything that likes bitmap is going to favor the Amiga anything that works best with tiles will favor the SNES/MD. But it has the CPU as the MD, just it doesn't have a cheap char mode. Amiga invented the FMV <img src="./images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";)" title="Wink" /> Also RAM, an A500 has at least 512K, 1MB is basically standard. 3MB is a rareish but not uncommon set up as well. <br />You can pull some fancy effects with bit-plane tricks, putting a shadow layer or colour inversion in the palette then move  single bitp-lane (shadow vectors). I would like to do the Donkey Kong Country Returns pure black foreground with colour background level idea on an Amiga. 1 bit-plane for the black, make half the palette black job done <img src="./images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";)" title="Wink" /> Sprites for colour accents. <br /><br />It would be interesting to see what an A500 could do with a tile based video chip on the expansion bus, it would technically have the same CPU as the MD, but if you can keep full access to the RAM then it would really open up the taps, if you can genlock it with the bitmap hardware like the Picasso and Video toaster boards did, really really powerful.<br /><br />If you want better than MD and SNES then you need to go AGA so Amiga 1200 or 4000 or CD32</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
